WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.000
Welcome to Understanding Quantum Information and Computation.

00:04.000 --> 00:08.000
My name is John Watrous, and I'm the Technical Director of IBM Quantum Education.

00:08.000 --> 00:14.000
The purpose of this series is to provide you with a solid understanding of quantum information and computation,

00:14.000 --> 00:18.000
and that means getting into the technical details of quantum information

00:18.000 --> 00:23.000
and seeing how quantum computing really works, what it can do, and what it can't do.

00:23.000 --> 00:28.000
If you haven't already watched the overview video for this series, I encourage you to check that out.

00:28.000 --> 00:34.000
In that video, you'll find information about what sort of background preparation is recommended for this series,

00:34.000 --> 00:38.000
as well as an outline of the topics to be covered.

00:38.000 --> 00:44.000
Also be sure to check out the Qiskit textbook, which covers the same material as this video series in a written form,

00:44.000 --> 00:48.000
and it also includes interactive components and interfaces to hardware and software

00:48.000 --> 00:53.000
designed to help you to better understand quantum information and computation.

00:53.000 --> 00:58.000
You'll find links to the overview video and the Qiskit textbook in the description.

00:58.000 --> 01:02.000
This is Lesson 1 of Unit 1 of the series.

01:02.000 --> 01:07.000
Unit 1 covers the basics of quantum information, and in the first lesson of this unit,

01:07.000 --> 01:11.000
we'll focus on how quantum information works for single systems,

01:11.000 --> 01:16.000
meaning that we have just one physical system or a device of some sort that stores quantum information,

01:16.000 --> 01:21.000
and we're considering how that one system or device works in isolation.

01:21.000 --> 01:27.000
In the lesson following this one, we'll discuss how quantum information works when we have multiple systems,

01:27.000 --> 01:31.000
and that will allow us to describe interesting and important concepts,

01:31.000 --> 01:35.000
such as quantum algorithms that make use of multiple qubits,

01:35.000 --> 01:40.000
and quantum protocols involving multiple individuals that process quantum information

01:40.000 --> 01:43.000
and transmit it back and forth to one another.

01:43.000 --> 01:45.000
But before getting into those discussions,

01:45.000 --> 01:51.000
it makes sense to start with the comparatively simple setting of a single system in isolation,

01:51.000 --> 01:55.000
partly because it's good to start simple, but also because, as we will see,

01:55.000 --> 01:59.000
the description of how quantum information works for single systems in isolation

01:59.000 --> 02:07.000
leads very naturally and logically to the description of how quantum information works for multiple systems.

02:07.000 --> 02:11.000
Here's a brief overview of the lesson.

02:11.000 --> 02:14.000
We're going to start by discussing classical information.

02:14.000 --> 02:19.000
Now, the purpose of this lesson is not to explain how classical information works,

02:19.000 --> 02:22.000
it's to explain how quantum information works.

02:22.000 --> 02:25.000
But to explain how quantum information works,

02:25.000 --> 02:28.000
it's very helpful to begin with classical information

02:28.000 --> 02:33.000
and to use it as a familiar point of reference when we discuss quantum information.

02:33.000 --> 02:39.000
At a mathematical level, quantum and classical information actually have pretty similar descriptions,

02:39.000 --> 02:42.000
with some key differences, of course.

02:42.000 --> 02:47.000
In fact, quantum information really isn't separate from classical information at all.

02:47.000 --> 02:50.000
It's an extension of classical information.

02:50.000 --> 02:53.000
The fact of the matter is, at least in my view,

02:53.000 --> 02:58.000
that you really can't understand quantum information if you don't understand classical information.

02:58.000 --> 03:02.000
So, starting with classical information makes sense.

03:02.000 --> 03:06.000
I do expect that this content will be familiar to some viewers,

03:06.000 --> 03:10.000
but even if you are familiar with it, I don't recommend that you skip it.

03:10.000 --> 03:13.000
In addition to highlighting the aspects of classical information

03:13.000 --> 03:16.000
that are most relevant to understanding quantum information,

03:16.000 --> 03:19.000
we're going to introduce the Dirac notation in this part,

03:19.000 --> 03:25.000
which is a standard way that we're going to use to describe vectors and matrices throughout the series.

03:25.000 --> 03:30.000
As it turns out, the Dirac notation isn't specific to quantum information.

03:30.000 --> 03:34.000
It can equally well be used in the context of classical information,

03:34.000 --> 03:39.000
as well as many other settings where vectors and matrices arise.

03:39.000 --> 03:41.000
We'll then move on to quantum information,

03:41.000 --> 03:46.000
and specifically we'll discuss the representation of quantum states as vectors,

03:46.000 --> 03:50.000
a simple type of measurement called a standard basis measurement,

03:50.000 --> 03:56.000
and unitary operations, which describe discrete time changes in quantum systems.

03:56.000 --> 04:00.000
Again, all in the setting of single systems.

04:02.000 --> 04:04.000
Before we get started with the lesson itself,

04:05.000 --> 04:10.000
it will be helpful to clarify that there are actually two descriptions of quantum information.

04:10.000 --> 04:14.000
The simplified description, which is what we'll be focusing on in this lesson

04:14.000 --> 04:16.000
and throughout this first unit,

04:16.000 --> 04:19.000
and the general description, which is covered in a later unit,

04:19.000 --> 04:23.000
specifically in the third unit of the series.

04:23.000 --> 04:29.000
The simplified description, true to its name, is simpler and it's typically learned first.

04:29.000 --> 04:32.000
In the simplified description, as I've already suggested,

04:32.000 --> 04:35.000
quantum states are represented by vectors,

04:35.000 --> 04:38.000
and operations are represented by unitary matrices.

04:38.000 --> 04:41.000
This description of quantum information is sufficient

04:41.000 --> 04:44.000
for an understanding of most quantum algorithms, for instance,

04:44.000 --> 04:48.000
so it isn't oversimplified, it's the real thing.

04:48.000 --> 04:54.000
However, as we will discover as we go along, it does have some limitations.

04:54.000 --> 04:59.000
For instance, if we want to model the effects of noise on quantum systems,

04:59.000 --> 05:03.000
this description turns out to be lacking.

05:03.000 --> 05:07.000
The general description, on the other hand, is more general,

05:07.000 --> 05:12.000
and ultimately it's more powerful in a mathematical sense.

05:12.000 --> 05:16.000
In this description, quantum states are represented by a special class of matrices

05:16.000 --> 05:19.000
called density matrices,

05:19.000 --> 05:23.000
and a more general class of measurements and operations can be described,

05:23.000 --> 05:26.000
including noise, for instance.

05:26.000 --> 05:29.000
It's entirely consistent with the simplified description,

05:29.000 --> 05:32.000
and in fact, you can essentially view the simplified description

05:32.000 --> 05:35.000
as a special case of the general description,

05:35.000 --> 05:39.000
and it also includes classical information as a special case.

05:39.000 --> 05:42.000
It's also really quite beautiful in how it all works.

05:42.000 --> 05:46.000
So, I strongly encourage you to learn about this general description

05:46.000 --> 05:50.000
when the time is right, but the simplified description is the more natural place to start,

05:50.000 --> 05:53.000
and so that is what we will do.

05:53.000 --> 05:56.000
We're going to begin by talking about classical information

05:56.000 --> 05:59.000
with an eye on the aspects of classical information

05:59.000 --> 06:02.000
that are most relevant to quantum information

06:02.000 --> 06:06.000
and the way that it's described mathematically.

06:06.000 --> 06:10.000
Imagine that we have a physical system or a device of some sort

06:10.000 --> 06:12.000
that stores information.

06:12.000 --> 06:15.000
We're going to give this system the name X,

06:15.000 --> 06:17.000
but there's nothing important about this name.

06:17.000 --> 06:20.000
We could use any other name if we preferred,

06:20.000 --> 06:24.000
so we're going to take a name we're going to call the system X.

06:24.000 --> 06:26.000
We're going to make an assumption about X,

06:26.000 --> 06:29.000
which is that there is a finite set of classical states

06:29.000 --> 06:33.000
that X can possibly be in at any given moment.

06:33.000 --> 06:36.000
Here, when I refer to a classical state,

06:36.000 --> 06:39.000
I mean a configuration of the system that can be recognized

06:39.000 --> 06:44.000
and described unambiguously without any uncertainty or error.

06:44.000 --> 06:47.000
Really, this is something that you can think about intuitively.

06:47.000 --> 06:51.000
At a mathematical level, we simply define the set of classical states.

06:51.000 --> 06:53.000
We choose it however we want to

06:53.000 --> 06:58.000
or in whatever way best describes the device that we're working with.

06:58.000 --> 07:02.000
Let us give the name sigma to this set of classical states,

07:02.000 --> 07:07.000
and again, let me emphasize that we're assuming that sigma is a finite set.

07:07.000 --> 07:10.000
The set of classical states of this system X is not infinitely large,

07:10.000 --> 07:12.000
like the set of all natural numbers.

07:12.000 --> 07:17.000
It's finite, and that's just an assumption that we're making.

07:17.000 --> 07:21.000
For example, it could be that X is a bit,

07:21.000 --> 07:27.000
in which case the classical state set is the set containing two elements, 0 and 1.

07:27.000 --> 07:31.000
Sometimes we refer to this set as the binary alphabet.

07:31.000 --> 07:35.000
Another example is that X is an ordinary six-sided die,

07:35.000 --> 07:40.000
in which case the classical states are the numbers 1 through 6.

07:40.000 --> 07:43.000
Of course, we're talking about an abstraction here.

07:43.000 --> 07:46.000
An actual six-sided die may have many different attributes,

07:46.000 --> 07:52.000
such as its precise position, its orientation, its temperature, and so on.

07:52.000 --> 07:56.000
But with respect to the information that's most typically relevant

07:56.000 --> 07:58.000
when we're talking about a six-sided die,

07:58.000 --> 08:01.000
the classical states are the numbers 1 through 6,

08:01.000 --> 08:07.000
indicated by the number of dots on whichever side of the die is facing up.

08:07.000 --> 08:12.000
If X is a switch on a standard sort of electric fan that you might have in your home,

08:12.000 --> 08:18.000
then perhaps the classical states are the settings high, medium, low, and off.

08:18.000 --> 08:20.000
These are just examples.

08:20.000 --> 08:23.000
We could imagine systems having different classical state sets than these,

08:23.000 --> 08:27.000
but hopefully they convey the idea that this notion of a classical state

08:27.000 --> 08:34.000
is something that should be familiar and can be understood in simple and intuitive terms.

08:34.000 --> 08:38.000
Mathematically speaking, the set of classical states is just a finite set.

08:38.000 --> 08:41.000
And of course, this set must also be non-empty as well.

08:41.000 --> 08:44.000
There has to be at least one classical state that the system can be in,

08:44.000 --> 08:47.000
and there has to be at least two classical states

08:47.000 --> 08:53.000
if the system is going to be useful at all for storing information.

08:53.000 --> 08:58.000
Now, in some situations, we might know that X is in some particular state,

08:58.000 --> 09:02.000
but in many situations that arise in the setting of information processing,

09:02.000 --> 09:07.000
there may be uncertainty about the classical state of a system at a particular moment,

09:07.000 --> 09:12.000
so that each possible classical state has some probability associated with it.

09:12.000 --> 09:19.000
For example, if X is a bit, then perhaps it's the case that X is in the classical state 0

09:19.000 --> 09:25.000
with probability 3 quarters, and it's in the state 1 with probability 1 quarter.

09:25.000 --> 09:29.000
We're going to refer to this as a probabilistic state,

09:29.000 --> 09:32.000
and we could express this probabilistic state as you see right here

09:32.000 --> 09:38.000
simply by indicating what the probabilities are for the different classical states.

09:38.000 --> 09:44.000
A more succinct way to express this probabilistic state is by a vector.

09:44.000 --> 09:49.000
Specifically, the representation that you see right here is a column vector,

09:49.000 --> 09:55.000
and this vector indicates what the probabilities are for the two possible classical states.

09:55.000 --> 10:01.000
To be more specific, the first entry indicates what the probability is for X to be in the state 0,

10:01.000 --> 10:06.000
and the second entry tells us what the probability is for the system to be in the state 1.

10:06.000 --> 10:10.000
This is simply the natural way to order the binary alphabet,

10:10.000 --> 10:16.000
or at least it's the way that we were trained to do this with 0 first and 1 second.

10:16.000 --> 10:22.000
Going forward, we're going to use the term probability vector to indicate a vector like this.

10:22.000 --> 10:26.000
Specifically, it's a vector whose entries are all non-negative real numbers

10:26.000 --> 10:29.000
and where the sum of the entries is equal to 1.

10:29.000 --> 10:34.000
So it makes sense to think about these entries as being probabilities.

10:34.000 --> 10:41.000
Here in this example, there are just two entries because there's just two classical states of the system we're talking about.

10:41.000 --> 10:43.000
But in general, there could be any number of entries,

10:43.000 --> 10:51.000
with the understanding being that there's one entry for each classical state of whatever system we're talking about.

10:51.000 --> 10:57.000
We're going to continue discussing classical information, probability vectors, and so on in just a moment.

10:57.000 --> 11:04.000
But first, it's going to be really helpful to introduce some notation for describing vectors known as the Dirac notation.

11:04.000 --> 11:08.000
In fact, this is just the first part of the Dirac notation.

11:08.000 --> 11:14.000
There are a couple of other aspects of the Dirac notation that we'll see a little bit later in the lesson.

11:14.000 --> 11:19.000
This notation is going to be quite central to the way that we describe quantum information,

11:19.000 --> 11:22.000
so it's essential to understand how it works.

11:22.000 --> 11:28.000
But fortunately, it's very simple and it really doesn't have anything specifically to do with quantum information.

11:28.000 --> 11:34.000
So we can introduce it now in the familiar context of classical information.

11:34.000 --> 11:40.000
As before, we assume that we have a set sigma of classical states of some system.

11:40.000 --> 11:44.000
And let's assume that we have an ordering of these classical states,

11:44.000 --> 11:49.000
just like how we refer to an ordering of the binary alphabet in the previous example.

11:49.000 --> 11:55.000
Another way of saying this is that the elements of sigma are placed in correspondence with the integers

11:55.000 --> 11:59.000
from one to however many elements are contained in sigma,

11:59.000 --> 12:03.000
which is what this notation right here with two bars around sigma means.

12:03.000 --> 12:06.000
That's the number of elements in the set sigma.

12:06.000 --> 12:11.000
So there's a first state, a second state, and so on.

12:11.000 --> 12:17.000
The specific ordering or correspondence that we choose isn't actually going to matter all that much.

12:17.000 --> 12:23.000
What's really important is that we have an ordering and we stick to it.

12:23.000 --> 12:27.000
For many classical state sets that we'll encounter, there will be a standard ordering,

12:27.000 --> 12:29.000
just like we have with the binary alphabet.

12:29.000 --> 12:33.000
And if there isn't a standard ordering, we can just choose one.

12:33.000 --> 12:40.000
But whatever it is, the understanding is that we stick to it.

12:40.000 --> 12:43.000
Now, here's the notation that's being introduced.

12:43.000 --> 12:47.000
For any choice of a classical state a from our set sigma,

12:47.000 --> 12:53.000
we write this right here, which is read as ket a to mean the column vector

12:53.000 --> 13:00.000
that has a one in the entry corresponding to a and a zero for all other entries.

13:00.000 --> 13:03.000
For example, if we return to the binary alphabet,

13:03.000 --> 13:09.000
which as you might have guessed is a very important example that we'll return to again and again,

13:09.000 --> 13:14.000
then ket zero and ket one are the vectors that are defined right here.

13:14.000 --> 13:20.000
Ket zero is the vector that has a one in the entry corresponding to the classical state zero,

13:20.000 --> 13:24.000
which is the first entry and a zero for all other entries.

13:24.000 --> 13:27.000
And in this case, there's only one other entry.

13:27.000 --> 13:32.000
Similarly, ket one is this vector right here where we have a one in the entry

13:32.000 --> 13:37.000
corresponding to one, which is the second entry and a zero for all other entries,

13:37.000 --> 13:41.000
which again is just one entry.

13:41.000 --> 13:43.000
Here's another example.

13:43.000 --> 13:48.000
In this example, we have a classical state set sigma corresponding to the four suits

13:48.000 --> 13:54.000
in a standard deck of playing cards, clubs, diamonds, hearts and spades.

13:54.000 --> 13:59.000
In this case, there really isn't a universally agreed upon ordering of these suits.

13:59.000 --> 14:02.000
For many card games, there is no ordering at all.

14:02.000 --> 14:05.000
They're just four different suits and that's all that matters.

14:05.000 --> 14:10.000
And there are different card games that do order these suits in different ways.

14:10.000 --> 14:11.000
But it doesn't really matter.

14:11.000 --> 14:15.000
We can just choose an ordering like the one that you see right here.

14:15.000 --> 14:22.000
This happens to be alphabetical ordering according to the names of these four suits written in English.

14:22.000 --> 14:27.000
Assuming that we've picked this particular ordering, then we define these four vectors,

14:27.000 --> 14:33.000
ket clubs, ket diamonds, ket hearts and ket spades, as you see right here.

14:33.000 --> 14:38.000
These vectors correspond to the general description that you see up here,

14:38.000 --> 14:43.000
given that we've chosen this particular ordering for these four suits.

14:43.000 --> 14:46.000
We can do the same thing for any classical state set that we choose,

14:46.000 --> 14:53.000
keeping in mind that classical state set always means finite and non-empty set.

14:53.000 --> 14:56.000
Vectors of this form are called standard basis vectors,

14:56.000 --> 15:01.000
and it's a very basic fact about vectors that every vector can be expressed in a unique way

15:01.000 --> 15:05.000
as a linear combination of standard basis vectors.

15:05.000 --> 15:10.000
For instance, going back to the example from just a moment ago,

15:10.000 --> 15:15.000
the probability vector we saw can be expressed as you see right here.

15:15.000 --> 15:19.000
It's basically just an alternative way of expressing vectors

15:19.000 --> 15:23.000
that's going to be very handy for several reasons going forward.

15:23.000 --> 15:25.000
And with that notation now in our hands,

15:25.000 --> 15:31.000
let's return to the discussion of classical information and probabilistic states in particular.

15:31.000 --> 15:38.000
And let's consider what happens when we measure a system while it's in some probabilistic state.

15:38.000 --> 15:43.000
We might not ordinarily refer to a measurement or the act of measuring something in the classical setting,

15:43.000 --> 15:45.000
but the term makes sense.

15:45.000 --> 15:49.000
In essence, when we talk about measuring the system X in this context,

15:50.000 --> 15:55.000
we just mean that we look at it and we recognize whatever state it's in.

15:55.000 --> 16:00.000
Of course, when we look at the system, we don't see a probabilistic state.

16:00.000 --> 16:02.000
We see a classical state.

16:02.000 --> 16:07.000
And the particular classical state that we see is one that we can imagine is chosen randomly

16:07.000 --> 16:09.000
according to the probabilities.

16:09.000 --> 16:14.000
Now, you might object on philosophical grounds to the idea that the classical state we see

16:14.000 --> 16:20.000
is somehow chosen at random at the moment that we measure or we look at the system.

16:20.000 --> 16:23.000
The system simply was in some particular classical state all along,

16:23.000 --> 16:27.000
and we just happen to have learned what the state was.

16:27.000 --> 16:31.000
But for the sake of thinking about the mathematical framework we're working with,

16:31.000 --> 16:33.000
it's okay to think about it this way,

16:33.000 --> 16:39.000
and doing so will allow us to draw a parallel with quantum information a little bit later.

16:39.000 --> 16:43.000
Let's suppose that the classical state that we see is the classical state A,

16:43.000 --> 16:46.000
which could be any state in our set sigma.

16:46.000 --> 16:52.000
This changes the probabilistic state of X in general, at least from our point of view.

16:52.000 --> 16:58.000
The probabilities no longer have any significance because we now know what the classical state of X is.

16:58.000 --> 17:03.000
It's A. And there's no longer any uncertainty about this.

17:03.000 --> 17:10.000
So we would now say this, that the probability that the system is in the state A is one.

17:10.000 --> 17:15.000
We know this because we just looked at it and we saw that the classical state is A.

17:15.000 --> 17:24.000
So the new probabilistic state of X is one in which the probability of being in the classical state A is equal to one.

17:24.000 --> 17:29.000
And that probabilistic state is represented by the probability vector ket A.

17:29.000 --> 17:35.000
We have a one in the entry corresponding to the classical state A and a zero in all other entries.

17:36.000 --> 17:43.000
For example, if we again consider the situation where X is a bit and we have the same probabilistic state as before,

17:43.000 --> 17:50.000
then if we measure X, we can imagine that a transition takes place.

17:50.000 --> 17:54.000
With probability three quarters, we see the classical state zero.

17:54.000 --> 17:59.000
And by measuring, we transition to ket zero being our probabilistic state.

17:59.000 --> 18:04.000
And with probability one quarter, we transition to ket one.

18:04.000 --> 18:10.000
You can think about this as a transition of knowledge, if you prefer, as opposed to an actual physical transition.

18:10.000 --> 18:16.000
But what's important for the sake of this lesson is to recognize how the mathematics works.

18:16.000 --> 18:19.000
It's kind of trivial, actually. But by recognizing this triviality,

18:19.000 --> 18:26.000
the analogous description for the quantum setting might seem a little bit less mysterious.

18:26.000 --> 18:33.000
One final note is that to another person who didn't happen to see what the classical state of X was when we measured it,

18:33.000 --> 18:38.000
the probabilistic state naturally wouldn't change as a result of us having measured it.

18:38.000 --> 18:43.000
That's OK. Different individuals can have different knowledge of a particular system

18:43.000 --> 18:50.000
and correspondingly choose different probabilistic states to represent their knowledge of that system.

18:50.000 --> 18:53.000
In the last part of this discussion of classical information,

18:53.000 --> 19:01.000
we'll talk about classical operations that can be performed on a system, starting with deterministic operations.

19:01.000 --> 19:06.000
When we perform an operation on a system, its state generally changes as a result.

19:06.000 --> 19:11.000
And in this context, the word deterministic means that the result of performing the operation

19:11.000 --> 19:19.000
depends entirely on whatever classical state the system was in prior to the operation being performed.

19:19.000 --> 19:24.000
In other words, there's no element of chance when a deterministic operation is performed,

19:24.000 --> 19:28.000
so there's no randomness or uncertainty involved.

19:28.000 --> 19:33.000
In mathematical terms, deterministic operations are described by functions.

19:33.000 --> 19:37.000
Every function F of the form that you see right here,

19:37.000 --> 19:44.000
which means that both the input and the output of the function correspond to elements of our classical state set sigma,

19:44.000 --> 19:46.000
describes a deterministic operation.

19:46.000 --> 19:53.000
The classical state A is transformed into the state F of A for each choice of a state A.

19:53.000 --> 20:01.000
For every function F of this form, there will always be a unique matrix M satisfying this condition that you see right here.

20:01.000 --> 20:08.000
And that is that by multiplying M to the vector ket A gives us the vector ket F of A.

20:08.000 --> 20:11.000
And that's true for every choice of a classical state A.

20:11.000 --> 20:17.000
It's not too hard to write down an explicit description of M given whatever function F of this form we've chosen.

20:17.000 --> 20:22.000
We'll always have exactly one one in each column with every other entry equal to zero.

20:22.000 --> 20:25.000
And here's the formula.

20:25.000 --> 20:32.000
The B A entry of M is equal to one if B is equal to F of A and otherwise it's equal to zero.

20:32.000 --> 20:41.000
And by this we mean this is the entry of M whose row corresponds to B and whose column corresponds to A.

20:41.000 --> 20:46.000
We'll see a few examples in just a moment and we'll see why this formula works.

20:46.000 --> 20:55.000
Now, it might not be clear why we would want to take a function and express it as a matrix like this, but it does make sense to do this.

20:55.000 --> 21:04.000
One of the reasons, and perhaps it's the main reason, is that if we have a system in a probabilistic state and we perform a deterministic operation on that system,

21:04.000 --> 21:10.000
then the resulting probabilistic state can be obtained by matrix vector multiplication.

21:11.000 --> 21:22.000
That is, if our system is in a probabilistic state that's represented by some probability vector V and we perform the deterministic operation described by M on that system,

21:22.000 --> 21:27.000
then the resulting probabilistic state will be given by M times V.

21:27.000 --> 21:38.000
Here, by the way, this arrow with a little bar on it like this is just a common notation in mathematics for indicating how one thing gets mapped to or transformed into another thing.

21:38.000 --> 21:43.000
You could just use an ordinary arrow, but this is conventional and it's recognizable.

21:43.000 --> 21:49.000
And maybe it's a little bit more specific than just an arrow, which could mean many different things.

21:49.000 --> 21:53.000
Now, let's take a look at an example or a collection of examples, really.

21:53.000 --> 22:00.000
Let's consider what happens when we take our classical state set sigma to be once again the binary alphabet.

22:00.000 --> 22:05.000
There aren't too many different functions of the form we've been discussing when this is our classical state set.

22:05.000 --> 22:09.000
And to be more precise, there are just four functions of this form.

22:09.000 --> 22:13.000
Here, those four functions are described by their so-called tables of values.

22:13.000 --> 22:19.000
The first table describes the first function, which we've named f1.

22:19.000 --> 22:24.000
For each possible input on the left, we list the corresponding output on the right.

22:24.000 --> 22:31.000
So f1 of zero is equal to zero and f1 of one is again equal to zero.

22:31.000 --> 22:34.000
And that is to say that f1 is the constant zero function.

22:34.000 --> 22:37.000
It always takes the value zero.

22:37.000 --> 22:41.000
The second function f2 is the identity function.

22:41.000 --> 22:46.000
The output is always equal to the input, as you can see from the second table.

22:46.000 --> 22:50.000
The third function f3 is described by the third table.

22:50.000 --> 22:55.000
f3 of zero is equal to one and f3 of one is equal to zero.

22:55.000 --> 23:01.000
This function is better known as the not function or logical negation.

23:01.000 --> 23:07.000
We sometimes also call it a bit flip because it flips zero to one and one to zero.

23:07.000 --> 23:12.000
The last function f4 is again a constant function just like the first one.

23:12.000 --> 23:17.000
But this one is the constant one function because it always takes the value one.

23:17.000 --> 23:22.000
And those are the only four functions from the binary alphabet to itself.

23:22.000 --> 23:26.000
Here are the four matrices that correspond to these four functions.

23:26.000 --> 23:31.000
They're described by the formula from before, which you can see right here.

23:31.000 --> 23:35.000
And if you're so inclined, you can pause the video and check this.

23:35.000 --> 23:41.000
Just remember that with matrices, the order of the indices is always rows first, columns second.

23:41.000 --> 23:46.000
So the BA entry corresponds to row B and column A,

23:46.000 --> 23:54.000
or the row that corresponds to the classical state B and the column that corresponds to the classical state A.

23:54.000 --> 24:01.000
So, for example, if we look at the first function, we have that f1 of zero is equal to zero.

24:01.000 --> 24:06.000
And correspondingly, the zero zero entry of m1 is equal to one.

24:06.000 --> 24:12.000
Well, the one zero entry, which is right here, is equal to zero.

24:12.000 --> 24:19.000
And you can do the same thing for the case where the input is equal to one and similarly for the other three functions.

24:19.000 --> 24:23.000
You can also check that this formula from before is true.

24:23.000 --> 24:28.000
And you can just go one by one through all the different possibilities to verify this.

24:28.000 --> 24:35.000
And in fact, if you think about the way that matrix multiplication works, really, you can just kind of eyeball this.

24:35.000 --> 24:41.000
When you multiply a matrix to a standard basis vector like this,

24:41.000 --> 24:46.000
you can imagine that you're taking the input and dropping it into the top of one of the matrices

24:46.000 --> 24:51.000
in whichever column corresponds to the classical state inside of the ket.

24:51.000 --> 24:56.000
And the output that you get is simply that column as a probability vector.

24:56.000 --> 25:06.000
So, for example, m3 multiplied to ket zero gives you zero one as a probability vector, which is ket one.

25:06.000 --> 25:13.000
m3 multiplied to ket one gives you one zero, which is ket zero, and so on.

25:13.000 --> 25:17.000
We'll discuss operations on probabilistic states more in just a moment.

25:17.000 --> 25:21.000
But first, let's introduce the second part of the Dirac notation.

25:21.000 --> 25:26.000
This is going to be helpful for talking about operations and thinking about them as matrices.

25:26.000 --> 25:30.000
It's also going to be a standard tool that we'll continue to use going forward.

25:30.000 --> 25:33.000
The setup is just like it was before.

25:33.000 --> 25:36.000
We have whatever classical state set sigma that we're working with,

25:36.000 --> 25:40.000
and we assume that we have some way of ordering those classical states.

25:40.000 --> 25:43.000
We then write this thing that you see right here,

25:43.000 --> 25:46.000
this time the angle bar is on the left rather than the right,

25:46.000 --> 25:51.000
to mean the row vector having a one in the entry that corresponds to A

25:51.000 --> 25:56.000
and a zero for all of the other entries corresponding to all the other classical states.

25:56.000 --> 26:03.000
So the difference between this thing and ket A is that this is a row vector and ket A is a column vector.

26:03.000 --> 26:07.000
But otherwise, the vectors are defined in a similar way.

26:07.000 --> 26:09.000
We read this as bra A.

26:09.000 --> 26:11.000
I'm not sure if that's supposed to be funny,

26:11.000 --> 26:16.000
but the idea is that the names bra and ket are two halves of the word bracket,

26:16.000 --> 26:19.000
and we'll have more to say about that in just a moment.

26:19.000 --> 26:23.000
But first, let's take a look at a very quick example.

26:23.000 --> 26:28.000
For the binary alphabet, we have that bra zero is this row vector right here,

26:28.000 --> 26:32.000
analogous to ket A, except it's a row vector instead of a column vector,

26:32.000 --> 26:36.000
and bra one is this vector right here.

26:37.000 --> 26:42.000
Now, in general, if we multiply a row vector to a column vector,

26:42.000 --> 26:47.000
just thinking about these as matrices that happen to have just one row or just one column,

26:47.000 --> 26:52.000
then we get a one by one matrix, which we can think about as being a scalar.

26:52.000 --> 26:59.000
Here, by the way, you should think about these stars as representing arbitrary numbers.

26:59.000 --> 27:05.000
In particular, if we multiply the row vector bra A to the column vector ket B,

27:05.000 --> 27:09.000
then there are two things that can happen.

27:09.000 --> 27:13.000
One is that A and B are equal, so they're the same classical state,

27:13.000 --> 27:19.000
in which case the ones will line up and the product will be equal to one.

27:21.000 --> 27:25.000
Or it could be the case that A and B are different,

27:25.000 --> 27:30.000
and so the ones don't line up and the product is equal to zero.

27:30.000 --> 27:35.000
A simple way of expressing these observations is like this right here.

27:35.000 --> 27:39.000
And just to keep things tidy, we write this product like this,

27:39.000 --> 27:45.000
with just one bar in the middle, and it means exactly the same thing as this right here.

27:45.000 --> 27:50.000
And now you can see how the bra and the ket go together to form a bracket,

27:50.000 --> 27:52.000
which is also called an inner product.

27:52.000 --> 27:57.000
And that's something that's quite important that we'll come back to in lesson number three.

27:57.000 --> 28:01.000
Multiplying a column vector to a row vector, on the other hand,

28:01.000 --> 28:05.000
gives us a matrix, as you can see right here.

28:05.000 --> 28:09.000
So, for example, going back yet again to the binary alphabet,

28:09.000 --> 28:16.000
if we multiply ket zero to bra zero, what we get is this matrix right here.

28:16.000 --> 28:20.000
And we can go through the other possibilities to see what happens.

28:20.000 --> 28:24.000
Ket zero times bra one gives us this matrix right here,

28:24.000 --> 28:27.000
where the one has now moved over to this position.

28:27.000 --> 28:30.000
Ket one, bra zero looks like this.

28:30.000 --> 28:34.000
And here's ket one, bra one.

28:34.000 --> 28:40.000
What we see happening is that there is just a single one in a matrix that's otherwise all zeros.

28:40.000 --> 28:47.000
And the position of that one is determined by which classical states we choose in the bra and the ket.

28:47.000 --> 28:52.000
More precisely, and this is true in general, for any choice of a classical state set,

28:52.000 --> 28:56.000
the matrix that we get by multiplying ket A to bra B

28:56.000 --> 29:02.000
is the matrix with a one in the AB entry and a zero for all other entries.

29:02.000 --> 29:06.000
And now that we have both the first and the second parts of the Dirac notation,

29:06.000 --> 29:10.000
we have a very handy tool for connecting operations with matrices.

29:10.000 --> 29:16.000
So let's go back briefly to deterministic operations and recall that a bit earlier in the lesson,

29:16.000 --> 29:20.000
it was stated that for every function F of this form right here,

29:20.000 --> 29:27.000
we have a deterministic operation that transforms A into F of A for each possible classical state A.

29:27.000 --> 29:30.000
And we said that for any function like this,

29:30.000 --> 29:36.000
there's always a unique matrix M that acts like this on standard basis states.

29:37.000 --> 29:43.000
Using the Dirac notation, we can now very easily express this matrix like you see right here.

29:43.000 --> 29:50.000
And we can see how sometimes it's possible to work with matrices entirely within the framework of the Dirac notation

29:50.000 --> 29:56.000
without ever explicitly converting to vectors and matrices, meaning rectangles filled with numbers.

29:56.000 --> 30:03.000
In this case, we can check that the required formula is true by multiplying M to ket A.

30:04.000 --> 30:07.000
We substitute our expression for M like this,

30:07.000 --> 30:14.000
and we can remove the parentheses and snap together the bra B with a ket A like this.

30:14.000 --> 30:20.000
And that's because matrix multiplication is linear in this case in the first argument and it's associative.

30:20.000 --> 30:23.000
So we can remove the parentheses.

30:23.000 --> 30:27.000
And now recalling that we have a fixed A that we're talking about,

30:27.000 --> 30:31.000
as we sum over all the possible choices of B,

30:31.000 --> 30:36.000
this bracket right here is always going to be equal to zero when B is not equal to A.

30:36.000 --> 30:39.000
So there won't be any contribution to the sum.

30:39.000 --> 30:43.000
And when B is equal to A, the bracket will be equal to one.

30:43.000 --> 30:47.000
And so we'll be left with this one term right here.

30:47.000 --> 30:49.000
That's the formula we wanted.

30:49.000 --> 30:54.000
And so we have a very nice and simple way of expressing a function as a matrix.

30:54.000 --> 30:56.000
In addition to deterministic operations,

30:56.000 --> 30:59.000
we also have operations that themselves introduce randomness

30:59.000 --> 31:03.000
or uncertainty about the classical state of a system.

31:03.000 --> 31:07.000
We use the term probabilistic operation to mean operations like this.

31:07.000 --> 31:10.000
And to be precise, when we say probabilistic operation,

31:10.000 --> 31:13.000
we mean operations that might introduce randomness.

31:13.000 --> 31:18.000
So deterministic operations are actually a special case of probabilistic operations

31:18.000 --> 31:22.000
that just don't happen to introduce any randomness.

31:22.000 --> 31:26.000
Here's a simple example where some randomness is introduced.

31:26.000 --> 31:29.000
This is an operation on a single bit.

31:29.000 --> 31:32.000
The way that it works is that if the classical state of the bit is a zero,

31:32.000 --> 31:35.000
then nothing happens. The bit stays as a zero.

31:35.000 --> 31:38.000
But if the classical state of the bit is a one,

31:38.000 --> 31:43.000
then the operation flips the bit to zero with probability equal to one half.

31:43.000 --> 31:46.000
There's no special name for this operation, at least not that I'm aware of.

31:46.000 --> 31:48.000
It's just an example.

31:48.000 --> 31:52.000
You could imagine performing this operation on a bit.

31:52.000 --> 31:54.000
Just like deterministic operations,

31:54.000 --> 31:57.000
probabilistic operations can be represented by matrices,

31:57.000 --> 32:02.000
and their actions on probabilistic states are given by matrix vector multiplication,

32:02.000 --> 32:04.000
just like before.

32:04.000 --> 32:08.000
This time it's not necessarily the case that the matrices have exactly one one

32:08.000 --> 32:11.000
in each column and zeros otherwise.

32:11.000 --> 32:16.000
Probabilistic operations are more generally represented by stochastic matrices.

32:16.000 --> 32:20.000
These are matrices whose entries are all non-negative real numbers

32:20.000 --> 32:23.000
and where the entries in each column sum to one.

32:23.000 --> 32:26.000
That's equivalent to saying that stochastic matrices are matrices

32:26.000 --> 32:30.000
where every column forms a probability vector.

32:30.000 --> 32:33.000
That makes sense when you think about the action of a matrix

32:33.000 --> 32:35.000
on a standard basis vector.

32:35.000 --> 32:37.000
You consider whatever classical state you wish,

32:37.000 --> 32:40.000
and you imagine dropping that state into the top of the matrix

32:40.000 --> 32:43.000
in whatever column corresponds to that classical state,

32:43.000 --> 32:46.000
and that column tells you what the probabilistic state is

32:46.000 --> 32:50.000
that comes out as a probability vector.

32:50.000 --> 32:53.000
The probabilistic operation in our example, for instance,

32:53.000 --> 32:56.000
is described by this matrix right here.

32:56.000 --> 32:59.000
If we perform this operation on the classical state zero,

32:59.000 --> 33:03.000
then the probabilistic state we get is given by the first column,

33:03.000 --> 33:06.000
which is, again, the classical state zero,

33:06.000 --> 33:11.000
or equivalently, the probabilistic state where zero occurs with probability one.

33:11.000 --> 33:14.000
If instead we perform this operation on the classical state one,

33:14.000 --> 33:17.000
then we effectively just randomize the bit,

33:17.000 --> 33:20.000
and correspondingly we get this probability vector here

33:20.000 --> 33:25.000
where the probability for each of the possible states is equal to one half.

33:27.000 --> 33:30.000
In general, if we perform this operation on any probabilistic state,

33:30.000 --> 33:34.000
then the effect is essentially just a weighted average between the two columns

33:34.000 --> 33:37.000
because that's how a matrix vector multiplication works.

33:37.000 --> 33:42.000
It's linear, so we just average the two possible outcomes accordingly.

33:44.000 --> 33:46.000
When we think about probabilistic operations in this way,

33:46.000 --> 33:51.000
it's natural to think about them as potentially introducing or injecting randomness.

33:51.000 --> 33:53.000
We can just read the columns one by one,

33:53.000 --> 33:57.000
and we can see the randomness that they introduce for each possible classical state.

33:58.000 --> 34:02.000
You can also think about probabilistic operations in a slightly different way,

34:02.000 --> 34:06.000
which is that they're random choices of deterministic operations.

34:07.000 --> 34:09.000
For instance, in our example,

34:09.000 --> 34:14.000
we can think about this operation as being equivalent to flipping a fair coin

34:14.000 --> 34:18.000
and either performing the constant zero function or the identity function,

34:18.000 --> 34:21.000
each with probability one half.

34:21.000 --> 34:24.000
And you can see that reflected right here by this equation.

34:24.000 --> 34:27.000
That's always possible for any probabilistic operation,

34:27.000 --> 34:29.000
and it's pretty intuitive.

34:29.000 --> 34:32.000
If you made random choices as part of some process,

34:32.000 --> 34:35.000
you could always imagine making those random choices in advance

34:35.000 --> 34:40.000
and then hard coding those choices into some collection of deterministic operations.

34:41.000 --> 34:44.000
It's sometimes quite helpful to think about probabilistic operations in this way,

34:44.000 --> 34:48.000
and we'll see an example of this down the road in a couple of lessons.

34:49.000 --> 34:52.000
The last thing to say about classical information for this lesson

34:52.000 --> 34:55.000
concerns composing probabilistic operations,

34:55.000 --> 34:58.000
which just means performing one after the other.

34:59.000 --> 35:02.000
Let's suppose that we have some system named X,

35:02.000 --> 35:05.000
and M1 through Mn are stochastic matrices

35:05.000 --> 35:08.000
representing probabilistic operations on X.

35:10.000 --> 35:13.000
Imagine first that we have a probability vector V,

35:13.000 --> 35:16.000
which represents a probabilistic state of X at some moment,

35:16.000 --> 35:19.000
and then we first apply the first probabilistic operation X,

35:19.000 --> 35:21.000
which is represented by the matrix M1,

35:21.000 --> 35:24.000
and then we apply the second probabilistic operation,

35:24.000 --> 35:26.000
which is represented by M2.

35:27.000 --> 35:29.000
If we do that, then the probability vector we get

35:29.000 --> 35:33.000
after applying just the first operation is M1 times V,

35:33.000 --> 35:36.000
and then when we apply the second operation,

35:36.000 --> 35:39.000
the resulting probability vector is M2 multiplied to

35:39.000 --> 35:42.000
whatever vector we obtained after applying M1,

35:42.000 --> 35:44.000
so it looks like this.

35:45.000 --> 35:49.000
Now, matrix multiplication is an associative operation,

35:49.000 --> 35:52.000
which means that it doesn't matter where we put these parentheses,

35:52.000 --> 35:55.000
so we could just as easily put the parentheses like this.

35:56.000 --> 35:58.000
That's very simple, but it's also interesting,

35:58.000 --> 36:01.000
because it reveals that we can think about the operation

36:01.000 --> 36:06.000
where we first apply M1 and then we apply M2 as a single operation.

36:08.000 --> 36:10.000
In other words, the probabilistic operation we get

36:10.000 --> 36:13.000
by composing the first and second probabilistic operation

36:13.000 --> 36:17.000
is represented by the matrix product, M2 times M1,

36:17.000 --> 36:21.000
and that's the same operation regardless of what probabilistic state we started with.

36:21.000 --> 36:24.000
We don't need to know anything about the probability vector V

36:24.000 --> 36:27.000
to think about or to describe this composed operation.

36:29.000 --> 36:33.000
Notice that the order here is M2 on the left and M1 on the right,

36:33.000 --> 36:35.000
which is because the matrix on the right, M1,

36:35.000 --> 36:37.000
is the one that gets multiplied to the vector V,

36:37.000 --> 36:43.000
whereas M2 gets multiplied to whatever vector we get after multiplying by M1.

36:43.000 --> 36:48.000
So we always have to keep in mind that the order in some sense gets reversed.

36:49.000 --> 36:51.000
The operation performed first is the one on the right,

36:51.000 --> 36:55.000
and the operation that gets performed last, or in this case second, is the one on the left.

36:57.000 --> 37:00.000
If we don't stop with the second operation and we apply all of them in order,

37:00.000 --> 37:03.000
starting with the first and ending with the last one, which is Mn,

37:03.000 --> 37:06.000
then the composition of all of these operations together

37:06.000 --> 37:09.000
is given by this product that you see right here.

37:10.000 --> 37:15.000
And you see that the ordering once again is reversed for exactly the same reason as before.

37:16.000 --> 37:19.000
So in short, compositions of probabilistic operations

37:19.000 --> 37:23.000
are represented by products of stochastic matrices that represent them,

37:23.000 --> 37:27.000
keeping in mind that this is the ordering of the matrices in the product.

37:28.000 --> 37:32.000
You will always get a stochastic matrix by taking a product of stochastic matrices like this,

37:32.000 --> 37:38.000
and sometimes we express this fact by saying that the stochastic matrices are closed under multiplication.

37:38.000 --> 37:42.000
And the way that you can think about this is that you can't get out of the set of stochastic matrices

37:42.000 --> 37:45.000
by multiplying them because the set is closed.

37:46.000 --> 37:49.000
Getting back to the ordering of the matrices in this product,

37:49.000 --> 37:52.000
it's important to note that the ordering really does matter.

37:52.000 --> 37:55.000
Matrix multiplication is not commutative.

37:55.000 --> 37:59.000
If you change the ordering of the matrices in the product, you might change the result.

37:59.000 --> 38:04.000
And we don't need to look any further than the deterministic operations to see this.

38:05.000 --> 38:08.000
Here's a simple example of two stochastic matrices,

38:08.000 --> 38:13.000
both of which represent deterministic operations where the ordering matters.

38:14.000 --> 38:17.000
M1 represents the constant 0 function,

38:17.000 --> 38:20.000
assuming we're imagining that these two operations are on bits,

38:20.000 --> 38:22.000
just like in the example from earlier.

38:23.000 --> 38:27.000
M2 represents the not operation or a bit flip.

38:29.000 --> 38:32.000
If you perform M1 first and then you perform M2,

38:32.000 --> 38:37.000
the result is this matrix right here, which represents the constant 1 function.

38:37.000 --> 38:42.000
If you set a bit to 0 and then you flip it, it's the same thing as just setting that bit to 1.

38:43.000 --> 38:47.000
On the other hand, if you perform M2 first and then you perform M1,

38:47.000 --> 38:49.000
this is the result right here.

38:50.000 --> 38:53.000
And this makes sense because if you flip a bit and then you set it to 0,

38:53.000 --> 38:57.000
it's the same thing as just setting it to 0. It didn't matter that you flipped it.

38:58.000 --> 39:00.000
Obviously, these two matrices are not the same,

39:00.000 --> 39:04.000
and so we have a very simple example revealing that the order does matter.

39:05.000 --> 39:07.000
Of course, this is not surprising at all.

39:07.000 --> 39:10.000
We all know that the order in which operations are performed matters,

39:10.000 --> 39:12.000
or at least it can matter.

39:12.000 --> 39:15.000
For example, if you light a match and then you blow on it,

39:15.000 --> 39:19.000
the result is very different from blowing on the match first and then lighting it.

39:20.000 --> 39:23.000
At this point, we've talked quite a lot about classical information,

39:23.000 --> 39:27.000
and now it's finally time to discuss quantum information.

39:27.000 --> 39:30.000
And what we'll find is that mathematically speaking,

39:30.000 --> 39:34.000
quantum information works in a very similar way to classical information,

39:34.000 --> 39:36.000
with some key differences.

39:37.000 --> 39:39.000
The first key difference is right at the start,

39:39.000 --> 39:43.000
how we define a state, in this case a quantum state of a system.

39:44.000 --> 39:48.000
And there is a sense in which this one choice, how we define a quantum state,

39:48.000 --> 39:51.000
largely determines how quantum information works.

39:53.000 --> 39:56.000
We'll also define how measurements and operations work,

39:56.000 --> 39:59.000
and in the next lesson we'll discuss how quantum information works

39:59.000 --> 40:02.000
not just for single systems, but for multiple systems.

40:03.000 --> 40:05.000
But these things actually follow pretty naturally

40:05.000 --> 40:10.000
once the notion of a quantum state of a single system in isolation has been established.

40:11.000 --> 40:13.000
Here's the definition.

40:13.000 --> 40:17.000
A quantum state of a system is represented by a column vector,

40:17.000 --> 40:21.000
whose indices are placed in correspondence with the classical states of that system.

40:21.000 --> 40:26.000
So we're assuming here that the system we're talking about has some set of classical states,

40:26.000 --> 40:30.000
just like when we talked about classical information and probabilistic states.

40:31.000 --> 40:34.000
The entries in a quantum state vector are complex numbers,

40:34.000 --> 40:39.000
as opposed to the probabilistic case where the entries are non-negative real numbers.

40:39.000 --> 40:44.000
And this time the sum of the absolute values squared of the entries must equal one,

40:44.000 --> 40:48.000
as opposed to the sum being equal to one, as we have in the probabilistic case.

40:50.000 --> 40:54.000
The complex numbers that appear in a quantum state vector are sometimes called amplitudes,

40:54.000 --> 40:57.000
and they play a role that's similar to probabilities,

40:57.000 --> 41:01.000
but they aren't probabilities and they don't have the same interpretation.

41:03.000 --> 41:07.000
Now, I can't give you a good reason for why quantum states should be defined like this,

41:07.000 --> 41:13.000
other than to say that physicists have discovered that this definition is physically relevant,

41:13.000 --> 41:17.000
and it allows us to describe and model quantum mechanical systems.

41:18.000 --> 41:21.000
In other words, we choose this definition because it works,

41:21.000 --> 41:26.000
not because there are any particular reasons why quantum states should be defined like this.

41:28.000 --> 41:32.000
With respect to the mathematics of this notion of a quantum state,

41:32.000 --> 41:36.000
the first step towards understanding it and working with it is to recall this definition

41:36.000 --> 41:39.000
for the Euclidean norm of a vector,

41:39.000 --> 41:42.000
which you can think of geometrically as the length of a vector,

41:42.000 --> 41:45.000
just like you would think about the length of a two-dimensional real vector

41:45.000 --> 41:51.000
if you drew it on a piece of paper as an arrow starting from the origin in the usual way.

41:52.000 --> 41:55.000
Specifically, if we have a column vector v like this,

41:55.000 --> 41:59.000
which we assume has complex number entries alpha-1 through alpha-n,

41:59.000 --> 42:04.000
then the Euclidean norm of v is defined like you see right here.

42:05.000 --> 42:07.000
This is the notation we use for the Euclidean norm,

42:07.000 --> 42:11.000
putting these double bars around whatever vector we're talking about.

42:11.000 --> 42:12.000
In this case, it's v.

42:12.000 --> 42:17.000
And the way the Euclidean norm is defined is that it's the square root of the sum

42:17.000 --> 42:21.000
of the absolute values squared of the entries of the vector.

42:22.000 --> 42:26.000
So, another way to define what a quantum state vector is,

42:26.000 --> 42:30.000
is that a quantum state vector is a column vector having complex number entries

42:30.000 --> 42:33.000
whose Euclidean norm is equal to 1,

42:33.000 --> 42:37.000
which is to say that it's a unit vector with respect to the Euclidean norm.

42:38.000 --> 42:41.000
That's because the sum of the absolute values squared is equal to 1

42:41.000 --> 42:44.000
if and only if the Euclidean norm is equal to 1.

42:44.000 --> 42:46.000
The square root doesn't change anything

42:46.000 --> 42:49.000
when the sum of the absolute values squared is equal to 1.

42:51.000 --> 42:53.000
So, that's what a quantum state vector is.

42:53.000 --> 42:57.000
It's a column vector with indices that correspond to the classical states of a system

42:57.000 --> 43:01.000
having complex number entries and Euclidean norm equal to 1.

43:03.000 --> 43:05.000
What that means, or what it implies,

43:05.000 --> 43:08.000
or how we should interpret this notion is a different matter.

43:09.000 --> 43:12.000
And in some sense, the study of quantum information and computation

43:12.000 --> 43:15.000
is an exploration of what this definition implies,

43:15.000 --> 43:18.000
at least in terms of information processing.

43:18.000 --> 43:20.000
This is simply the starting point.

43:22.000 --> 43:25.000
As an aside, let me mention that there are other so-called norms

43:25.000 --> 43:27.000
besides the Euclidean norm,

43:27.000 --> 43:30.000
and this notation right here with the double bars around a vector

43:30.000 --> 43:33.000
doesn't always mean the Euclidean norm.

43:33.000 --> 43:37.000
In different contexts, this notation could refer to a different norm.

43:38.000 --> 43:43.000
For example, the sum of the absolute values with no squares or square root

43:43.000 --> 43:46.000
is a different norm, often called the one norm.

43:46.000 --> 43:49.000
There are quite a lot of different norms, in fact.

43:50.000 --> 43:53.000
Sometimes you'll see this notation being used with a subscript

43:53.000 --> 43:56.000
after the second set of bars that provides more information

43:56.000 --> 43:58.000
about what norm we're talking about.

43:58.000 --> 44:00.000
And when we do that, it's pretty typical

44:00.000 --> 44:04.000
that the number 2 as a subscript means the Euclidean norm.

44:05.000 --> 44:09.000
But in this series, whenever we have a column vector like this,

44:09.000 --> 44:13.000
this double bar notation all by itself means the Euclidean norm.

44:15.000 --> 44:17.000
Here are a few examples of quantum state vectors,

44:17.000 --> 44:21.000
and these particular quantum state vectors are qubit state vectors,

44:21.000 --> 44:25.000
which means that the classical states of our system are 0 and 1.

44:26.000 --> 44:28.000
The word qubit is short for quantum bit,

44:28.000 --> 44:32.000
which is really just a bit that can be in a quantum state.

44:34.000 --> 44:36.000
The first two examples are really simple.

44:36.000 --> 44:41.000
The standard basis vectors ket 0 and ket 1 are quantum state vectors.

44:42.000 --> 44:43.000
They're both column vectors,

44:43.000 --> 44:47.000
and the indices correspond to the classical states 0 and 1,

44:47.000 --> 44:50.000
and the entries of these vectors are complex numbers.

44:51.000 --> 44:53.000
For these particular vectors, the entries are 0 and 1,

44:53.000 --> 44:56.000
which are real numbers, and in fact they're integers,

44:56.000 --> 45:01.000
but they're also complex numbers that happen to have imaginary part equal to 0.

45:02.000 --> 45:06.000
Each vector has one entry equal to 1 and one entry equal to 0,

45:06.000 --> 45:11.000
so when we sum the absolute values of the entries, we get 1 in both cases.

45:11.000 --> 45:16.000
So, the conditions required for these vectors to be quantum state vectors are satisfied.

45:19.000 --> 45:22.000
The next two examples are very commonly encountered qubit states

45:22.000 --> 45:25.000
called the plus state and the minus state.

45:25.000 --> 45:28.000
They're denoted as you see here on the screen,

45:28.000 --> 45:31.000
either with a ket plus or a ket minus like this,

45:31.000 --> 45:33.000
and they're defined as you can see right here.

45:34.000 --> 45:37.000
Again, the entries of these vectors are complex numbers.

45:37.000 --> 45:41.000
This time they're either positive 1 over square root of 2 or negative 1 over square root of 2,

45:41.000 --> 45:46.000
and when we sum the absolute values squared, we get 1 half plus 1 half, which is 1.

45:47.000 --> 45:52.000
By the way, putting a plus sign or a minus sign inside of a ket like this might seem a little strange

45:52.000 --> 45:55.000
because these aren't classical states of our system,

45:55.000 --> 45:59.000
but this notation is used nevertheless and we'll come back to this momentarily.

46:00.000 --> 46:06.000
But for now, in short, we can use the Dirac notation to put whatever name we want for a vector inside of a ket.

46:06.000 --> 46:11.000
The vector doesn't have to be a standard basis vector when we use the Dirac notation.

46:13.000 --> 46:16.000
Here's a final qubit state example for the moment anyway.

46:16.000 --> 46:22.000
It's a quantum state vector of a qubit that doesn't have a special name and it's not particularly significant.

46:23.000 --> 46:28.000
The entries of this vector are 1 plus 2 times i over 3 and negative 2 thirds.

46:29.000 --> 46:33.000
These are complex numbers and if you compute the absolute values squared of these two entries,

46:33.000 --> 46:37.000
you'll get 5 ninths for the first one and 4 ninths for the second one.

46:38.000 --> 46:41.000
So the sum of the absolute values squared is equal to 1.

46:44.000 --> 46:49.000
And here's one last example, this time for a system whose classical states are the four card suits.

46:50.000 --> 46:55.000
I don't know why we would have a system whose classical states are the four card suits being in a quantum state,

46:55.000 --> 46:59.000
but it is possible in principle and it's just meant as an example.

47:01.000 --> 47:05.000
The entries corresponding to the different suits are 1 half for clubs,

47:05.000 --> 47:10.000
negative i over 2 for diamonds, 0 for hearts because it doesn't appear in the sum,

47:10.000 --> 47:13.000
and 1 over square root of 2 for spades.

47:14.000 --> 47:17.000
And here's what it looks like as a column vector,

47:17.000 --> 47:20.000
assuming that we've ordered the classical states as we did before,

47:20.000 --> 47:23.000
which is the order that you see right here.

47:24.000 --> 47:27.000
Taking the absolute value squared of these entries gives 1 quarter for the first one,

47:27.000 --> 47:29.000
also 1 quarter for the next one.

47:29.000 --> 47:34.000
The absolute value squared of 0 is equal to 0, so that entry doesn't contribute to the sum.

47:34.000 --> 47:37.000
And finally for the last one, we get 1 half.

47:37.000 --> 47:42.000
So the sum is equal to 1, as is required for this vector to be a quantum state vector.

47:43.000 --> 47:49.000
Now, just a moment ago, we used the notation ket plus and ket minus to refer to two qubit state vectors

47:49.000 --> 47:51.000
that aren't standard basis vectors,

47:51.000 --> 47:57.000
and I'd like to return to this point briefly and explain how the Dirac notation is used for arbitrary vectors

47:57.000 --> 48:00.000
and not just for standard basis vectors.

48:00.000 --> 48:06.000
As I've already mentioned, we can use whatever name we want inside of a bra or ket to refer to a vector.

48:06.000 --> 48:11.000
Kets are column vectors and bras are row vectors, just like before.

48:12.000 --> 48:19.000
As an example, the Greek letter psi is very commonly used inside of a ket to refer to some arbitrary vector,

48:19.000 --> 48:25.000
and here we're using it to give a name to the state vector from before that doesn't have a special name.

48:25.000 --> 48:29.000
When we do this, the letter psi doesn't necessarily have any meaning all by itself.

48:29.000 --> 48:35.000
It's just the name of a vector, and it's inside of a ket to help us to clarify that it's a column vector.

48:36.000 --> 48:40.000
This can be a little bit confusing sometimes, and there is a potential for ambiguity

48:40.000 --> 48:44.000
if the letter psi could be associated with a classical state of some system, for instance,

48:44.000 --> 48:47.000
but it generally doesn't cause any problems.

48:48.000 --> 48:51.000
And you don't have to use the Dirac notation like this if you don't want to.

48:51.000 --> 48:58.000
Using a lowercase letter such as u, v, or w without a ket is also a fine way to denote a column vector,

48:58.000 --> 49:01.000
or more specifically, a quantum state vector.

49:01.000 --> 49:05.000
It's your choice what notation you use to express yourself.

49:05.000 --> 49:10.000
You just need to make sure that number one, the meaning of what you're trying to express is clear to others,

49:10.000 --> 49:13.000
and number two, that you understand what others are trying to express

49:13.000 --> 49:17.000
even when their preferences for notation aren't the same as yours.

49:18.000 --> 49:22.000
There is one very important rule for using the Dirac notation for arbitrary vectors,

49:22.000 --> 49:27.000
and that is that if you have a column vector that you've decided to write as ket psi, for instance,

49:27.000 --> 49:29.000
or it could be a different name inside of a ket,

49:29.000 --> 49:35.000
then the row vector bra psi is understood to be the conjugate transpose of the vector ket psi,

49:35.000 --> 49:41.000
and here this is written as an equation where this dagger right here refers to the conjugate transpose.

49:42.000 --> 49:46.000
What that is specifically is the row vector you get by, number one, transposing the vector,

49:46.000 --> 49:50.000
meaning that you flip the vector on its side and you change it from a column into a row

49:50.000 --> 49:52.000
without actually changing the entries,

49:52.000 --> 49:56.000
and number two, taking the complex conjugate of each of the entries.

49:56.000 --> 50:00.000
You can actually perform those two operations, the transpose and the entry-wise complex conjugate,

50:00.000 --> 50:03.000
in either order, those two operations commute.

50:04.000 --> 50:09.000
So, for the vector in this example, given that we've decided to call this vector ket psi,

50:09.000 --> 50:13.000
it's understood that bra psi means this vector right here,

50:13.000 --> 50:18.000
where we've transposed the vector by turning ket zero and ket one into bra zero and bra one,

50:18.000 --> 50:21.000
and we've taken the complex conjugate of each entry,

50:21.000 --> 50:27.000
which is why one plus two times i over three turns into one minus two times i over three right here.

50:28.000 --> 50:33.000
Here's what these vectors look like when they're written explicitly as a column vector and a row vector.

50:33.000 --> 50:37.000
Notice, by the way, that this rule is consistent with the notation we use

50:37.000 --> 50:40.000
when we have classical states inside of the bra and the ket.

50:40.000 --> 50:43.000
In that case, the entries are all zero except for one one,

50:43.000 --> 50:47.000
and so taking the complex conjugate doesn't do anything in that case.

50:48.000 --> 50:52.000
We've now seen how quantum states are represented as vectors,

50:52.000 --> 50:56.000
but it's not clear at this point what the meaning or the implications are

50:56.000 --> 51:01.000
in terms of what you can do with a system in a quantum state or how you can interact with it.

51:01.000 --> 51:06.000
The first thing we need to do to bring these issues into focus is to discuss measurements.

51:07.000 --> 51:14.000
Intuitively speaking, measurements provide a mechanism for extracting classical information from quantum systems.

51:14.000 --> 51:18.000
When we look at a system when it's in a quantum state, we don't see a quantum state,

51:18.000 --> 51:21.000
just like we don't see probabilistic states.

51:21.000 --> 51:26.000
We see classical states, and this notion of a measurement is what provides the interface.

51:27.000 --> 51:31.000
If we as humans want to know something about a quantum system, we have to measure it,

51:31.000 --> 51:37.000
and in doing so, we'll extract classical information about whatever quantum state that system was in.

51:38.000 --> 51:40.000
There are different notions of measurements.

51:40.000 --> 51:43.000
The difference is one of generality, really,

51:43.000 --> 51:49.000
and we're going to start with the simplest and most basic one, which is typically called a standard basis measurement.

51:50.000 --> 51:52.000
We will generalize this in subsequent lessons.

51:52.000 --> 51:55.000
We'll talk about so-called projective measurements in lesson three,

51:55.000 --> 51:59.000
and then later on in the third unit of the series, we'll talk about general measurements,

51:59.000 --> 52:04.000
which are also called positive operator-valued measures, or POVMs for short.

52:05.000 --> 52:09.000
But for now, we'll restrict our attention to standard basis measurements.

52:10.000 --> 52:15.000
When a measurement is performed on a system, there will be some set of possible outcomes of that measurement,

52:15.000 --> 52:19.000
which are classical outcomes, and in the case of a standard basis measurement,

52:19.000 --> 52:24.000
those possible outcomes are precisely the classical states of whatever system is being measured.

52:25.000 --> 52:29.000
Each of those classical states will be the outcome of the measurement with some probability,

52:29.000 --> 52:34.000
and that probability is the absolute value squared of the entry corresponding to that classical state

52:34.000 --> 52:39.000
of whatever quantum state vector the system was in immediately prior to being measured.

52:40.000 --> 52:44.000
We know that the absolute value squared of any complex number is a non-negative real number,

52:44.000 --> 52:49.000
and we know from the definition of quantum state vectors that the sum of the absolute value squared

52:49.000 --> 52:52.000
of the entries of a quantum state vector is equal to one.

52:52.000 --> 52:54.000
So this makes sense.

52:54.000 --> 52:58.000
Each classical state will appear as the outcome of the measurement with some probability,

52:58.000 --> 53:00.000
and the probabilities sum to one.

53:00.000 --> 53:02.000
Here are a few examples.

53:03.000 --> 53:06.000
First, suppose we have a qubit in the plus state.

53:07.000 --> 53:10.000
If we measure this qubit with respect to a standard basis measurement,

53:10.000 --> 53:13.000
we get either a zero or a one as the outcome.

53:14.000 --> 53:19.000
The probability of getting a zero is the absolute value squared of one over root two, which is one half,

53:19.000 --> 53:21.000
and that's the same probability of getting a one.

53:22.000 --> 53:26.000
So, if you measure a plus state, you'll get a uniform random bit.

53:27.000 --> 53:30.000
If the system is in a minus state rather than a plus state,

53:30.000 --> 53:32.000
then measuring works in exactly the same way.

53:32.000 --> 53:36.000
The probabilities are again one half for each possible outcome.

53:36.000 --> 53:40.000
The only difference here is that the plus sign turned into a minus sign,

53:40.000 --> 53:43.000
but when we take the absolute value, nothing changes.

53:44.000 --> 53:46.000
If we measure this qubit state,

53:46.000 --> 53:51.000
the probability to get the outcome zero is the absolute value squared of one plus two times i over three,

53:51.000 --> 53:53.000
which is five ninths,

53:53.000 --> 53:59.000
and the probability to get the outcome one is the absolute value squared of negative two thirds, which is four ninths.

54:00.000 --> 54:05.000
And finally, measuring the standard basis state ket zero gives the outcome zero with certainty,

54:05.000 --> 54:10.000
and likewise measuring the state ket one yields the outcome one with certainty.

54:10.000 --> 54:13.000
That's because the absolute value squared of one is one.

54:14.000 --> 54:16.000
Similar to what we had in the probabilistic setting,

54:16.000 --> 54:19.000
we can associate these quantum states, ket zero and ket one,

54:19.000 --> 54:22.000
with the system being in those classical states,

54:22.000 --> 54:25.000
and this example is consistent with that interpretation.

54:26.000 --> 54:29.000
Now, just like we had in the probabilistic setting,

54:29.000 --> 54:32.000
if we measure a system when it's in a quantum state,

54:32.000 --> 54:37.000
then the state will change in general as a result of having performed that measurement.

54:38.000 --> 54:42.000
In particular, and again this is exactly like we had in the probabilistic setting,

54:42.000 --> 54:46.000
if we measure a system and the outcome of the measurement is the classical state A,

54:46.000 --> 54:50.000
then the new quantum state of the system becomes ket A.

54:50.000 --> 54:53.000
So, for this state right here, for instance,

54:53.000 --> 54:57.000
we see the same kind of behavior that we had in the probabilistic setting.

54:57.000 --> 55:00.000
If we measure, then with probability five ninths,

55:00.000 --> 55:04.000
we obtain the outcome zero, in which case the state transitions to ket zero.

55:04.000 --> 55:07.000
And with probability four ninths, the outcome is one,

55:07.000 --> 55:10.000
and the state transitions to ket one.

55:10.000 --> 55:14.000
Sometimes this phenomenon is referred to as a collapse of the quantum state,

55:14.000 --> 55:19.000
and it's the kind of thing that keeps people that study the foundations of quantum mechanics awake at night.

55:19.000 --> 55:23.000
But from a purely mathematical perspective, it's really quite simple

55:23.000 --> 55:27.000
and very much analogous to what we have in the probabilistic case.

55:28.000 --> 55:32.000
The source of tension here, in some sense, concerns the fundamental nature of quantum states

55:32.000 --> 55:36.000
and what they represent and how they differ from probabilistic states.

55:36.000 --> 55:40.000
But at a mathematical level, this is perhaps what you might expect.

55:41.000 --> 55:44.000
Notice, by the way, that if you measured a second time,

55:44.000 --> 55:47.000
then you would get exactly the same result as you did for the first measurement.

55:48.000 --> 55:52.000
So there's a limit on how much classical information can be extracted from a quantum state,

55:52.000 --> 55:56.000
and we'll come back to this point soon in another lesson.

55:57.000 --> 56:00.000
We've talked about quantum states as well as measurements,

56:00.000 --> 56:02.000
specifically standard basis measurements,

56:02.000 --> 56:07.000
which provide a way to extract classical information from quantum states.

56:08.000 --> 56:11.000
The remaining topic for this lesson is operations,

56:11.000 --> 56:13.000
specifically unitary operations,

56:13.000 --> 56:17.000
which describe how quantum states of systems can be changed.

56:18.000 --> 56:22.000
Naturally, given that quantum state vectors are different from probability vectors,

56:22.000 --> 56:26.000
you would expect that set of allowable operations on quantum states

56:26.000 --> 56:29.000
is different than what we have for classical information,

56:29.000 --> 56:31.000
and indeed that's the case.

56:32.000 --> 56:37.000
Whereas operations on probabilistic states are represented by stochastic matrices,

56:37.000 --> 56:41.000
operations on quantum state vectors are represented by unitary matrices.

56:42.000 --> 56:45.000
Here's the definition of unitary matrices.

56:46.000 --> 56:49.000
The square matrix U having complex number entries is unitary

56:49.000 --> 56:53.000
if it satisfies the equalities that you see right here.

56:54.000 --> 56:56.000
The dagger represents the conjugate transpose,

56:56.000 --> 57:01.000
which we already saw for vectors when we talked about the Dirac notation a few moments ago.

57:02.000 --> 57:06.000
Here we're performing the conjugate transpose on a matrix rather than a vector,

57:06.000 --> 57:08.000
but it's essentially the same thing.

57:09.000 --> 57:13.000
We transpose the matrix, which just means that we swap rows and columns,

57:13.000 --> 57:16.000
so the jk entry becomes the kj entry,

57:16.000 --> 57:20.000
and also we take the complex conjugate of each entry.

57:21.000 --> 57:24.000
Also, this notation right here means the identity matrix.

57:25.000 --> 57:28.000
These two equalities right here are actually equivalent.

57:28.000 --> 57:31.000
If you have one, then you automatically have the other.

57:31.000 --> 57:34.000
They're both equivalent to saying that U is invertible

57:35.000 --> 57:38.000
and the inverse is equal to the conjugate transpose.

57:39.000 --> 57:41.000
That's only true for square matrices, by the way.

57:41.000 --> 57:43.000
If you have a matrix that isn't square,

57:43.000 --> 57:46.000
then one of those two equalities might be true,

57:46.000 --> 57:48.000
but then the other one won't be true.

57:49.000 --> 57:51.000
But here we're talking about square matrices.

57:52.000 --> 57:55.000
So this is the standard definition for unitary matrices,

57:55.000 --> 57:59.000
and it's nice because it's easy to check if a matrix is unitary.

57:59.000 --> 58:03.000
You just multiply the matrix to its conjugate transpose on either side,

58:03.000 --> 58:06.000
and you see if you get the identity matrix.

58:08.000 --> 58:10.000
There's an equivalent way to characterize unitary matrices,

58:10.000 --> 58:14.000
and that is that a square matrix is unitary if and only if

58:14.000 --> 58:18.000
it never changes the Euclidean norm of any vector when you multiply.

58:19.000 --> 58:24.000
An n-by-n matrix U is unitary if and only if the Euclidean norm of U times V

58:24.000 --> 58:26.000
is equal to the Euclidean norm of V

58:26.000 --> 58:30.000
for every n-dimensional column vector V with complex number entries.

58:30.000 --> 58:33.000
And therefore, if V is a quantum state vector,

58:33.000 --> 58:36.000
then U times V is also a quantum state vector,

58:36.000 --> 58:41.000
because quantum state vectors are simply the vectors having Euclidean norm equal to 1.

58:42.000 --> 58:44.000
In fact, we can say a little bit more,

58:44.000 --> 58:47.000
which is that the unitary matrices are precisely the matrices

58:47.000 --> 58:51.000
that always transform quantum state vectors into quantum state vectors.

58:52.000 --> 58:56.000
That's a similar situation to what we have for stochastic matrices and probability vectors.

58:56.000 --> 58:59.000
The stochastic matrices are precisely the matrices

58:59.000 --> 59:03.000
that always transform probability vectors into probability vectors.

59:04.000 --> 59:08.000
So, once we've decided that operations should be represented by matrices,

59:08.000 --> 59:13.000
which is the same as saying that transformations act linearly on vectors representing states,

59:13.000 --> 59:17.000
these choices for the sets of allowable operations follow naturally,

59:17.000 --> 59:19.000
at least in a mathematical sense.

59:21.000 --> 59:25.000
Now let's take a look at some examples of qubit unitary operations.

59:25.000 --> 59:30.000
We'll see many more examples of unitary operations in subsequent lessons,

59:30.000 --> 59:34.000
including unitary operations on systems having more than two classical states,

59:34.000 --> 59:38.000
but for now we'll focus just on qubit unitary operations.

59:39.000 --> 59:42.000
We're going to be seeing these particular examples arising again and again,

59:42.000 --> 59:45.000
so it's definitely worth getting to know these operations.

59:47.000 --> 59:50.000
The first collection of examples are the so-called polyoperations.

59:50.000 --> 59:55.000
These are the operations that correspond to the polymatrices, which are shown here.

59:56.000 --> 01:00:01.000
They're all unitary, and you can check that for each one according to the definition from before.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:07.000
These particular matrices happen to be equal to their own conjugate transposes,

01:00:07.000 --> 01:00:10.000
which is to say that they're all Hermitian matrices.

01:00:10.000 --> 01:00:14.000
So, checking that they're all unitary in this case is a matter of squaring each one

01:00:14.000 --> 01:00:17.000
and seeing that the result is the identity matrix.

01:00:18.000 --> 01:00:21.000
The names you see for these matrices are pretty standard,

01:00:21.000 --> 01:00:27.000
and you'll also see sigma x, sigma y, and sigma z called simply x, y, and z.

01:00:28.000 --> 01:00:33.000
Do be aware, though, that the capital letters x, y, and z are also commonly used for other purposes,

01:00:33.000 --> 01:00:36.000
even in the context of quantum information,

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:39.000
but they are very common names for these matrices.

01:00:40.000 --> 01:00:45.000
The sigma x, or x operation, is also called a bit flip, or a knot operation,

01:00:45.000 --> 01:00:48.000
which we've already seen in the classical context,

01:00:48.000 --> 01:00:52.000
and the sigma z, or z operation, is also called a phase flip.

01:00:52.000 --> 01:00:57.000
And here you can see the action of these operations on the standard basis vectors,

01:00:57.000 --> 01:01:00.000
which kind of explains where these names come from.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:05.000
Certainly it makes sense to refer to sigma x as a bit flip based on this action right here.

01:01:05.000 --> 01:01:09.000
It simply flips the bit from 0 to 1, or 1 to 0.

01:01:10.000 --> 01:01:15.000
It also makes sense to call sigma z a phase flip based on this action right here,

01:01:15.000 --> 01:01:18.000
but if that's not crystal clear at the moment, that's okay.

01:01:18.000 --> 01:01:20.000
We'll encounter this operation over and over,

01:01:20.000 --> 01:01:26.000
and the significance of putting a minus sign in front of the ket 1 basis vector and not ket 0

01:01:26.000 --> 01:01:29.000
and why that's called a phase flip will be more clear later on.

01:01:30.000 --> 01:01:32.000
The next example is the Hadamard operation,

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:35.000
which is represented by this matrix right here,

01:01:35.000 --> 01:01:37.000
which is pretty much always named H.

01:01:39.000 --> 01:01:43.000
Checking that H is unitary is, once again, a straightforward calculation,

01:01:43.000 --> 01:01:46.000
which, if I step out of the way, you can see right here.

01:01:47.000 --> 01:01:50.000
Similar to the Pauli matrices, H is its own conjugate transpose,

01:01:50.000 --> 01:01:53.000
so we have this equality right here,

01:01:53.000 --> 01:01:58.000
and when we perform the multiplication, we get the identity matrix, as is required.

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:05.000
The third example is really an entire class of unitary operations known as phase operations.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:09.000
These are operations represented by any matrix that takes this form that you see right here,

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:11.000
where theta is any real number.

01:02:12.000 --> 01:02:17.000
So this entry right here will always be some complex number on the unit circle.

01:02:18.000 --> 01:02:22.000
Matrices like this are always unitary, which I will leave to you to verify.

01:02:23.000 --> 01:02:26.000
This time, the conjugate transpose won't be equal to the original matrix

01:02:26.000 --> 01:02:29.000
unless this number here happens to be a 1 or a minus 1,

01:02:29.000 --> 01:02:33.000
in which case we end up with either the identity matrix or sigma z,

01:02:33.000 --> 01:02:35.000
which we've already encountered.

01:02:36.000 --> 01:02:39.000
Specifically, transposition won't do anything to this matrix,

01:02:39.000 --> 01:02:45.000
but taking the complex conjugate of each entry changes this entry right here to e to the minus i theta.

01:02:47.000 --> 01:02:52.000
These two particular operations right here are particularly important examples of phase operations.

01:02:53.000 --> 01:02:57.000
For the first one, we take theta to be pi over 2, and we get this matrix right here.

01:02:58.000 --> 01:03:02.000
This is commonly called an S operation or an S gate when we're talking about circuits,

01:03:02.000 --> 01:03:06.000
which we won't discuss in this lesson, but that's an important topic that's coming up soon.

01:03:07.000 --> 01:03:11.000
The second one is this operation. It's a T operation or a T gate.

01:03:11.000 --> 01:03:15.000
And for this one, theta is equal to pi over 4, and so when we compute the exponential,

01:03:15.000 --> 01:03:19.000
we get this value right here, which is 1 plus i over the square root of 2.

01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:24.000
Here are just a few quick examples to see a couple of these operations in action.

01:03:25.000 --> 01:03:29.000
Here's the action of the Hadamard operation on ket 0 and ket 1.

01:03:29.000 --> 01:03:36.000
If we go through the matrix-spectre multiplication, we see that what we obtain are the plus state and the minus state, respectively.

01:03:38.000 --> 01:03:42.000
If we perform the Hadamard operation on the plus state and the minus state on the other hand,

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:45.000
we get back to ket 0 and ket 1.

01:03:46.000 --> 01:03:50.000
So if we clean things up a little bit, we can see the action more clearly.

01:03:51.000 --> 01:03:56.000
The Hadamard operation transforms back and forth between the 0 state and the plus state

01:03:56.000 --> 01:03:59.000
and between the 1 state and the minus state.

01:04:00.000 --> 01:04:08.000
Concerning these two equations right here, notice that this gives us a simple way to detect the difference between a plus state and a minus state.

01:04:09.000 --> 01:04:15.000
As we saw earlier in the lesson, if we measure a plus state and a minus state with respect to the standard basis measurement,

01:04:15.000 --> 01:04:20.000
we get a uniform random bit in both cases, which doesn't help us to detect the difference.

01:04:21.000 --> 01:04:30.000
But if we perform a Hadamard operation and then we measure, we'll see a 0 if the original state was a plus state and a 1 if the original state was a minus state.

01:04:31.000 --> 01:04:37.000
So these two states are indeed different and they can be discriminated perfectly by the method that I just described,

01:04:37.000 --> 01:04:41.000
which is to first perform a Hadamard operation and then to measure.

01:04:43.000 --> 01:04:48.000
Going back to the example of a qubit state we saw before that isn't particularly special,

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:56.000
we can see what the Hadamard operation does to the state by converting to the forms that you see right here and performing the multiplication.

01:04:57.000 --> 01:05:02.000
And here is the result, which we can convert back to the Dirac notation if we wish.

01:05:03.000 --> 01:05:06.000
And that's one way to compute these sorts of actions.

01:05:07.000 --> 01:05:12.000
Here's another example that illustrates that you don't always have to convert explicitly to a matrix vector form.

01:05:13.000 --> 01:05:17.000
You can also perform these computations directly using the Dirac notation.

01:05:18.000 --> 01:05:23.000
This example concerns the T operation and here it is right here just for reference.

01:05:25.000 --> 01:05:29.000
This operation has this action right here on standard basis states.

01:05:30.000 --> 01:05:34.000
And if we want to compute the action of the T operation on a plus state, for instance,

01:05:35.000 --> 01:05:42.000
we can start by expanding the definition of the plus state and then use linearity to express the result as you see right here.

01:05:43.000 --> 01:05:51.000
We can now just plug in these expressions up here, do just a little bit of simplification for the second term, and we obtain the result.

01:05:53.000 --> 01:05:59.000
If for whatever reason we'd like to apply a Hadamard operation to the result, we can do a similar thing.

01:06:00.000 --> 01:06:06.000
First, we substitute the expression for T acting on the plus state and we use linearity like we did before.

01:06:06.000 --> 01:06:14.000
And now if we substitute the expressions we already have for the Hadamard operation acting on ket zero and ket one, we obtain this.

01:06:16.000 --> 01:06:23.000
And now we can expand the plus state and the minus state to get this expression right here, which we can simplify just by adding.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:25.000
And here is the final result.

01:06:27.000 --> 01:06:29.000
There's nothing particularly special about this example.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:35.000
It's just meant to illustrate this alternative but equivalent way of calculating the actions of these operations.

01:06:36.000 --> 01:06:39.000
You can use whichever way is more convenient in the situation at hand.

01:06:40.000 --> 01:06:49.000
One final point about unitary operations is that compositions of unitary operations are represented by matrix multiplication, just like in the probabilistic setting.

01:06:51.000 --> 01:06:56.000
That is, you can compute the action of a sequence of unitary operations by simply multiplying the matrices together.

01:06:57.000 --> 01:07:03.000
And what you'll get is a single unitary matrix representing the combined action of the sequence of operations.

01:07:04.000 --> 01:07:10.000
Just like we had for stochastic matrices, the unitary matrices are closed under multiplication.

01:07:11.000 --> 01:07:15.000
So you'll always get a unitary matrix when you compose unitary operations.

01:07:16.000 --> 01:07:23.000
You have to make sure you multiply the matrices in the correct order, but the way it works is just like it was for stochastic operations,

01:07:24.000 --> 01:07:31.000
where the matrix for the first operation you perform will always appear on the right-hand side of the matrix product and the last one will appear on the left-hand side.

01:07:31.000 --> 01:07:38.000
So just like before, the order is reversed in the sense that you compose from right to left rather than left to right.

01:07:40.000 --> 01:07:46.000
Here's an interesting example that gives rise to an operation known as the square root of not operation.

01:07:48.000 --> 01:07:54.000
Suppose that we first apply a Hadamard operation, followed by an S operation, followed by another Hadamard operation.

01:07:55.000 --> 01:07:59.000
The combined action of these three operations is described by this product.

01:08:00.000 --> 01:08:06.000
Here's the first Hadamard operation, here's the S operation, and here's the second Hadamard operation.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:16.000
If we perform the matrix multiplication, which isn't shown here explicitly, but you can do this for yourself if you wish, the result is this matrix right here.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:24.000
It's a unitary matrix, and we can either check that directly or we can trust in the fact that the unitary matrices are closed under multiplication.

01:08:25.000 --> 01:08:30.000
It has to be unitary because these three matrices are unitary as we've already seen.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:35.000
We don't have any particular quantum state vector in mind here.

01:08:35.000 --> 01:08:42.000
We can imagine performing this sequence of operations on any quantum state vector, and this matrix describes the action.

01:08:44.000 --> 01:08:51.000
The reason why this combined operation, meaning the one described by this matrix right here, is called a square root of not operation,

01:08:51.000 --> 01:08:57.000
is that by performing it twice, we get a not operation, or in other words, a sigma x or an x operation.

01:08:59.000 --> 01:09:08.000
Performing the operation twice is represented by squaring the matrix or multiplying it to itself, and if you do this, you'll see that the result is the poly x matrix.

01:09:09.000 --> 01:09:17.000
And that's kind of peculiar, and it gives you just a hint that you can do some interesting things with quantum information that you can't do with classical information.

01:09:18.000 --> 01:09:25.000
There's no classical operation, meaning one represented by a stochastic matrix, that gives us a not operation if we perform it twice.

01:09:26.000 --> 01:09:32.000
So it's a nice example that reveals that quantum operations behave very differently from classical operations.

01:09:33.000 --> 01:09:40.000
And that's it for lesson one. In this lesson, we discussed how quantum information works for single systems in isolation,

01:09:41.000 --> 01:09:45.000
and in the next lesson, we'll talk about how quantum information works for multiple systems.

01:09:45.000 --> 01:09:50.000
Thanks for watching. If you have any questions, feel free to leave them in the comments section below.

